00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:09.764
We should do something
before they do.

769
00:34:22.944 --> 00:34:24.528
[panting]

770
00:34:28.616 --> 00:34:30.660
[grunting softly]

771
00:34:30.701 --> 00:34:33.246
[sniffles]

772
00:34:33.287 --> 00:34:36.832
[Dexter] <i>Nice. a three-mile
hike up to the iron mine.</i>

773
00:34:36.874 --> 00:34:39.835
<i>'Cause I just
don't get out enough.</i>

774
00:34:45.466 --> 00:34:48.052
So what's the deal
with you and your dad?

775
00:34:48.094 --> 00:34:49.929
Before you showed up here.
he never mentioned you.

776
00:34:49.971 --> 00:34:52.682
<i>When I come again...</i>

777
00:34:52.723 --> 00:34:54.850
Mm. It's not worth going into.

778
00:34:54.892 --> 00:34:57.103
What's the deal
with you and yours?

779
00:34:57.144 --> 00:34:59.563
Um... he's dead.

780
00:34:59.605 --> 00:35:01.649
Oh.

781
00:35:03.192 --> 00:35:05.194
I'm-I'm sorry.

782
00:35:05.236 --> 00:35:07.613
It was a long time ago.

783
00:35:07.655 --> 00:35:09.657
I barely remember him.

784
00:35:09.699 --> 00:35:12.076
And my birth mom? Nothing.

785
00:35:12.118 --> 00:35:13.619
Wait. Wait. Angela's not...

786
00:35:13.661 --> 00:35:15.621
The woman who gave birth to me

787
00:35:15.663 --> 00:35:17.707
abandoned me
right after I was born.

788
00:35:17.748 --> 00:35:20.126
So Angela is my mom.

789
00:35:23.546 --> 00:35:25.673
[Harrison]
That your guitar in the back?

790
00:35:27.091 --> 00:35:28.968
It was my Dad's.

791
00:35:29.010 --> 00:35:31.137
I love playing it knowing
he held it in his hands.

792
00:35:32.722 --> 00:35:34.056
[engine rattling]

793
00:35:34.098 --> 00:35:36.142
Oh. and this fucking car
was his. too.

794
00:35:36.183 --> 00:35:37.810
- What's wrong?
- [groans] Damn it.

795
00:35:37.852 --> 00:35:39.854
[brakes squeaking]

796
00:35:40.813 --> 00:35:43.566
Probably
the damn radiator again.

797
00:35:50.364 --> 00:35:52.491
Yep.

798
00:35:52.533 --> 00:35:54.577
Radiator hose split.

799
00:35:54.618 --> 00:35:57.330
[sighs]
Got to replace it.

800
00:35:57.371 --> 00:35:59.832
What. you know how
to do this shit?

801
00:35:59.874 --> 00:36:01.667
My mom's paranoid
about everything.

802
00:36:01.709 --> 00:36:02.918
Made me learn
how to change a tire

803
00:36:02.960 --> 00:36:04.628
as soon as I got
my learner's permit.

804
00:36:15.139 --> 00:36:16.974
Great.

805
00:36:17.016 --> 00:36:18.976
No bars.

806
00:36:19.018 --> 00:36:20.853
[sighs]

807
00:36:20.895 --> 00:36:23.147
You mind going down that road
and calling Jerry's Auto Shop?

808
00:36:23.189 --> 00:36:24.690
Yeah.

809
00:36:24.732 --> 00:36:27.318
- The number's in my phone.
- Okay.

810
00:36:27.360 --> 00:36:29.487
Tell him I need

811
00:36:29.528 --> 00:36:32.573
a three-inch wide. two-foot long
radiator hose and two clamps.

812
00:36:32.615 --> 00:36:34.367
- I got you.
- I'll pop this hose off

813
00:36:34.408 --> 00:36:35.743
so we can
get out of here sooner.

814
00:36:35.785 --> 00:36:38.204
All right. All right.

815
00:36:41.082 --> 00:36:43.125
[panting]

816
00:37:10.236 --> 00:37:11.487
<i>[Tonettes' "My Heart Can
Feel the Pain" playing]</i>

817
00:37:11.529 --> 00:37:14.698
<i>♪ My heart can feel the pain ♪</i>

818
00:37:14.740 --> 00:37:15.991
<i>[women vocalizing]</i>

819
00:37:18.244 --> 00:37:20.746
Everything all right?

820
00:37:21.747 --> 00:37:23.457
Radiator.

821
00:37:23.499 --> 00:37:25.376
Oh. I. um...

822
00:37:25.418 --> 00:37:27.169
Do you need a ride someplace?

823
00:37:27.211 --> 00:37:28.963
My friend's just up
that hill calling for help.

824
00:37:29.004 --> 00:37:30.673
- Uh-huh.
- He should be back soon.

825
00:37:30.714 --> 00:37:32.883
Well. do you want to wait
in my car until he gets back?

826
00:37:32.925 --> 00:37:35.428
It's warm. Sodas. TV.

827
00:37:35.469 --> 00:37:37.054
I know who you are. Mr. Olsen.

828
00:37:37.096 --> 00:37:38.848
I know the tonnage of CO2

829
00:37:38.889 --> 00:37:40.808
your chemical plants
release every year.

830
00:37:40.850 --> 00:37:43.769
The millions you've spent
fighting climate science.

831
00:37:43.811 --> 00:37:45.896
Want to be helpful?

832
00:37:45.938 --> 00:37:47.690
Stop fucking up the planet.

833
00:37:47.731 --> 00:37:49.442
Oh. my.

834
00:37:49.483 --> 00:37:52.611
You know. I find it funny
that you hate me so much.

835
00:37:52.653 --> 00:37:55.614
and here you are
driving this old gas-guzzler.

836
00:37:55.656 --> 00:37:58.617
Some might consider
that hypocritical. but I don't.

837
00:37:58.659 --> 00:38:00.953
People are complicated.

838
00:38:00.995 --> 00:38:03.247
Life's complicated.

839
00:38:03.289 --> 00:38:06.709
One day you'll understand
how the world really works.

840
00:38:08.377 --> 00:38:10.546
You have a good day. Audrey.

841
00:38:10.588 --> 00:38:12.756
Stay safe.

842
00:38:17.636 --> 00:38:20.264
- Any luck?
- [engine starts]

843
00:38:20.306 --> 00:38:21.682
The minute I mentioned
your mom's name.

844
00:38:21.724 --> 00:38:23.225
Jerry was halfway to his truck.

845
00:38:23.267 --> 00:38:25.478
- [exhales]
- [engine revs]

846
00:38:25.519 --> 00:38:28.105
<i>[song playing faintly]</i>

847
00:38:28.147 --> 00:38:30.649
What was that about?

848
00:38:30.691 --> 00:38:33.652
Just Edward Olsen
being a billionaire.

849
00:38:36.655 --> 00:38:38.699
[grunts]

850
00:38:45.915 --> 00:38:48.000
[grunts]

851
00:39:11.565 --> 00:39:13.359
[stammering]

852
00:39:20.241 --> 00:39:22.159
[grunts]

853
00:39:22.826 --> 00:39:25.871
[Dexter] <i>Mine's not the body
I'm looking to hide.</i>

854
00:39:41.262 --> 00:39:43.055
[rock thuds faintly]

855
00:39:44.014 --> 00:39:45.266
<i>Okay.</i>

856
00:39:45.307 --> 00:39:46.308
<i>This'll work.</i>

857
00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:47.726
[sighs]

858
00:39:49.853 --> 00:39:52.106
<i>I miss this.</i>

859
00:39:52.147 --> 00:39:53.941
<i>The quiet.</i>

860
00:39:53.983 --> 00:39:55.734
<i>Calm.</i>

861
00:39:56.902 --> 00:39:58.904
<i>Solitude.</i>

862
00:39:58.946 --> 00:40:00.948
[bear growling]

863
00:40:03.617 --> 00:40:06.495
- [panting]
- [roaring]

864
00:40:06.537 --> 00:40:07.746
Fuck!

865
00:40:07.788 --> 00:40:09.915
[panting]

866
00:40:11.792 --> 00:40:12.960
Fuck!

867
00:40:16.130 --> 00:40:17.840
[phone buzzing]

868
00:40:17.881 --> 00:40:19.758
[grunts]

869
00:40:25.389 --> 00:40:27.433
[exhales]

870
00:40:28.976 --> 00:40:30.853
Hey. you. What's up?

871
00:40:30.894 --> 00:40:33.439
Just seeing if you want
to come over for dinner tonight.

872
00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:36.066
Tonight? Uh...

873
00:40:36.108 --> 00:40:38.277
I'm not sure I'm up for it.

874
00:40:38.319 --> 00:40:40.946
I'm kind of exhausted.
Rain check?

875
00:40:40.988 --> 00:40:42.948
I know. I'm exhausted. too.

876
00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:45.993
You think I feel like cooking
for Audrey and Harrison?

877
00:40:46.035 --> 00:40:48.287
- Harrison?
- <i>Yeah.</i>

878
00:40:48.329 --> 00:40:50.080
<i>Audrey invited him over.</i>

879
00:40:50.122 --> 00:40:51.749
[mouthing]

880
00:40:53.292 --> 00:40:55.294
If you don't want to come.
it's okay.

881
00:40:55.336 --> 00:40:57.171
No. I'd love to come.

882
00:40:57.212 --> 00:40:59.340
I'll come.

883
00:41:02.593 --> 00:41:05.095
[ringing]

884
00:41:06.847 --> 00:41:08.390
Sup. Eeth?

885
00:41:08.432 --> 00:41:10.225
<i>I wanted to thank you for today.</i>

886
00:41:10.267 --> 00:41:11.435
Yeah. don't worry about it.

887
00:41:11.477 --> 00:41:12.811
<i>I've always fantasized</i>

888
00:41:12.853 --> 00:41:14.813
<i>about hurting Zach like that.</i>

889
00:41:14.855 --> 00:41:16.982
but you actually did.

890
00:41:17.024 --> 00:41:18.942
[chuckles]
Fuck those guys.

891
00:41:18.984 --> 00:41:20.903
They just think they're hard
'cause they hunt and shit.

892
00:41:20.944 --> 00:41:23.489
Uh. they don't know anything
about real violence.

893
00:41:23.530 --> 00:41:25.783
<i>I got a bunch of drawings
of those assholes.</i>

894
00:41:25.824 --> 00:41:27.660
<i>You want to see?</i>

895
00:41:27.701 --> 00:41:29.411
Thrill me.

896
00:41:47.554 --> 00:41:50.182
[chuckles] What are you. like.
The Punisher or something?

897
00:41:50.224 --> 00:41:53.977
[scoffs] <i>They'd be fucking
scared of me if I was. huh?</i>

898
00:41:54.019 --> 00:41:56.355
<i>Fucking petrified.</i>

899
00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:01.402
[sighs]

900
00:42:01.443 --> 00:42:03.487
- [indistinct chatter]
- [fire crackling]

901
00:42:06.323 --> 00:42:09.159
- [dog barks]
- [Dexter] <i>Bears. dogs.</i>

902
00:42:09.201 --> 00:42:11.578
<i>I miss the days
when the only animals</i>

903
00:42:11.620 --> 00:42:13.664
<i>I had to worry about
were alligators.</i>

904
00:42:13.706 --> 00:42:15.791
[sighs]

905
00:42:15.833 --> 00:42:17.543
And Rusty's dogs spent the day

906
00:42:17.584 --> 00:42:19.294
literally barking
up the wrong tree.

907
00:42:19.336 --> 00:42:20.963
They couldn't find
shit out there.

908
00:42:21.004 --> 00:42:23.298
I saw. I mean.
what do you think it means?

909
00:42:23.340 --> 00:42:26.135
I don't know. but I'm going
to meet Rusty and his dogs

910
00:42:26.176 --> 00:42:27.720
at the crime scene tomorrow.

911
00:42:27.761 --> 00:42:29.221
What do you mean. you saw?

912
00:42:29.263 --> 00:42:30.848
On the <i>Merry Fucking Kill</i>
Instagram.

913
00:42:30.889 --> 00:42:33.058
Can you believe Molly Park is
in Iron Lake?

914
00:42:33.100 --> 00:42:35.227
Who's Molly Park?

915
00:42:42.359 --> 00:42:44.236
Oh. you got
to be fucking kidding me.

916
00:42:44.278 --> 00:42:46.238
[stammers]
Let me see that again?

917
00:42:47.531 --> 00:42:49.241
She was in the store today.

918
00:42:49.283 --> 00:42:51.410
She was loading up
on winter gear.

919
00:42:51.452 --> 00:42:54.079
I guess she's sticking around
for a while.

920
00:42:54.121 --> 00:42:56.123
Wait. so...

921
00:42:56.165 --> 00:42:58.125
so she's a podcaster?

922
00:42:58.167 --> 00:42:59.376
It's only. like.
the most popular

923
00:42:59.418 --> 00:43:01.086
true crime podcast out there.

924
00:43:01.128 --> 00:43:03.046
I mean. she has. like. a million
followers on Instagram.

925
00:43:03.088 --> 00:43:04.423
You're into true crime?

926
00:43:04.465 --> 00:43:06.258
It's murder. but it's funny.

927
00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:08.135
I'll text you my top five.

928
00:43:14.516 --> 00:43:16.435
So...

929
00:43:16.477 --> 00:43:18.896
I got a call
from Abraham Brown today.

930
00:43:20.689 --> 00:43:22.691
He said you guys took
a little drive

931
00:43:22.733 --> 00:43:24.943
out to the Reservation.

932
00:43:24.985 --> 00:43:27.529
Did you think
I wasn't gonna find out?

933
00:43:27.571 --> 00:43:30.282
I was trying
to do the right thing.

934
00:43:30.324 --> 00:43:31.617
By going behind my back?

935
00:43:31.658 --> 00:43:32.576
The way that deer's
being treated is.

936
00:43:32.618 --> 00:43:34.077
like. totally fucked...

937
00:43:34.119 --> 00:43:35.704
messed up.

938
00:43:35.746 --> 00:43:38.248
Even though it's dead.
it still deserves dignity.

939
00:43:38.290 --> 00:43:40.083
[Angela]
I agree.

940
00:43:40.125 --> 00:43:41.752
[Audrey] Then why didn't
you do something?

941
00:43:41.794 --> 00:43:44.296
Um. I'm in the middle
of a criminal investigation.

942
00:43:44.338 --> 00:43:45.714
I've been a little busy.

943
00:43:49.092 --> 00:43:50.886
Audz. next time. just come to me

944
00:43:50.928 --> 00:43:52.554
and we can find
a solution together.

945
00:43:52.596 --> 00:43:54.473
This isn't some
parenting Jedi Mind Trick.

946
00:43:54.515 --> 00:43:57.017
This is me on your side.

947
00:43:59.853 --> 00:44:01.980
[Audrey]
I spoke with Abraham.

948
00:44:02.022 --> 00:44:04.399
We came up with a plan
for the deer.

949
00:44:04.441 --> 00:44:06.318
Just need you to release it.

950
00:44:06.360 --> 00:44:09.154
Hmm. Say we are done with it.

951
00:44:09.196 --> 00:44:11.615
What's the plan?

952
00:44:11.657 --> 00:44:12.991
- [Audrey] Gonna do a bonfire...
- [Dexter] <i>Who'd have thought</i>

953
00:44:13.033 --> 00:44:14.535
<i>I would find this.</i>

954
00:44:14.576 --> 00:44:16.745
<i>A family in Iron Lake.</i>

955
00:44:16.787 --> 00:44:18.914
<i>A family that I very nearly lost</i>

956
00:44:18.956 --> 00:44:20.916
<i>because of an impulsive kill.</i>

957
00:44:20.958 --> 00:44:22.459
<i>I don't want to lose this.</i>

958
00:44:22.501 --> 00:44:24.211
[Harrison] ...Jim would
drive his tractor...

959
00:44:24.253 --> 00:44:25.671
[Dexter] <i>All that's left is
to find a spot to...</i>

960
00:44:25.712 --> 00:44:27.172
[Harrison]
...move the body.

961
00:44:27.214 --> 00:44:28.966
What?

962
00:44:29.007 --> 00:44:30.843
Y-You could help us

963
00:44:30.884 --> 00:44:32.678
move the deer's body. right?

964
00:44:32.719 --> 00:44:34.346
Your-your truck bed's
big enough?

965
00:44:34.388 --> 00:44:36.515
Yeah. Should be.

966
00:44:38.058 --> 00:44:40.018
Hmm. Sounds like a plan.

967
00:44:40.060 --> 00:44:42.145
Great.
'Cause I already told them

968
00:44:42.187 --> 00:44:44.106
we'd be doing it tonight.

969
00:45:03.208 --> 00:45:05.210
<i>Nya: weh sgëno'.</i>

970
00:45:06.712 --> 00:45:08.547
<i>Nya: weh.</i> Angela.

971
00:45:08.589 --> 00:45:10.340
Thank you for agreeing to this.

972
00:45:10.382 --> 00:45:11.884
Of course.

973
00:45:18.390 --> 00:45:20.934
<i>[speaking Seneca]</i>

974
00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:36.992
[Dexter]
<i>Humans have always</i>

975
00:45:37.034 --> 00:45:39.578
<i>dealt with death
through rituals.</i>

976
00:45:39.620 --> 00:45:41.914
<i>Guess mine are just
a little unique.</i>

977
00:45:43.248 --> 00:45:45.292
Hey. we should go.

978
00:45:47.252 --> 00:45:51.256
<i>Look at them...
as close as people can be.</i>

979
00:45:51.298 --> 00:45:53.425
<i>And here I stand. ten feet</i>

980
00:45:53.467 --> 00:45:56.261
<i>and 1.000 miles away
from my own son.</i>

981
00:46:02.309 --> 00:46:04.603
I should've stood up for you

982
00:46:04.645 --> 00:46:06.939
at school yesterday.

983
00:46:08.357 --> 00:46:10.108
I was wrong.

984
00:46:11.401 --> 00:46:13.445
Yeah. you were.

985
00:46:15.822 --> 00:46:18.450
Well. from now on.
this is me on your side.

986
00:46:25.666 --> 00:46:27.292
Thanks. Dad.

987
00:46:28.335 --> 00:46:31.713
[Dexter]
<i>"Dad." Wow.</i>

988
00:46:31.755 --> 00:46:33.590
<i>My new favorite word.</i>

989
00:46:33.632 --> 00:46:35.717
[exhales]

990
00:46:35.759 --> 00:46:37.719
<i>[gentle. eerie music]</i>

991
00:46:42.641 --> 00:46:44.977
<i>I only wish
the rest of my problems</i>

992
00:46:45.018 --> 00:46:47.312
<i>would go up in smoke.</i>

993
00:46:47.354 --> 00:46:49.398
<i>Wait a minute.</i>

994
00:46:54.778 --> 00:46:56.822
[grunting]

995
00:47:05.205 --> 00:47:07.165
<i>Finally.</i>

996
00:47:07.207 --> 00:47:09.334
<i>Rid of Matt's body for good.</i>

997
00:47:17.342 --> 00:47:20.095
<i>And now back to abstaining.</i>

998
00:47:28.812 --> 00:47:30.856
- [bolt slides]
- [exhales]

999
00:47:32.607 --> 00:47:34.693
[fire roaring. crackling]

1000
00:47:42.534 --> 00:47:44.453
<i>But I don't know.</i>

1001
00:47:44.494 --> 00:47:47.080
<i>What if it's not the killing
that got me in trouble?</i>

1002
00:47:48.248 --> 00:47:50.500
<i>What if it's the not killing?</i>

1003
00:47:53.086 --> 00:47:54.880
[whoops]

1004
00:47:57.007 --> 00:48:00.052
<i>That does not look
like a grieving father.</i>

1005
00:48:00.093 --> 00:48:02.387
[whooping]

1006
00:48:02.429 --> 00:48:05.223
- [Kurt laughing]
- <i>What's wrong with this picture?</i>

1007
00:48:07.059 --> 00:48:10.228
[Kurt muttering]
What'd I do with the...?

1008
00:48:11.563 --> 00:48:12.814
There we go.

1009
00:48:12.856 --> 00:48:14.900
Hey. Kurt.

1010
00:48:17.152 --> 00:48:18.737
Oh. hey. man.

1011
00:48:18.779 --> 00:48:20.363
Hey. Hey.

1012
00:48:20.405 --> 00:48:22.282
Did you hear my news?

1013
00:48:22.324 --> 00:48:24.076
No. What's the news?

1014
00:48:24.117 --> 00:48:25.494
He's alive.

1015
00:48:25.535 --> 00:48:26.953
[laughs softly]
Yeah.

1016
00:48:26.995 --> 00:48:29.372
Matty's alive.

1017
00:48:29.414 --> 00:48:31.958
H-How do you know?

1018
00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:33.752
Well. he-he called me.

1019
00:48:33.794 --> 00:48:36.004
And we had the best talk.

1020
00:48:36.046 --> 00:48:38.256
Really great talk.

1021
00:48:38.298 --> 00:48:40.467
Must've been amazing
to hear his voice.

1022
00:48:40.509 --> 00:48:44.054
Oh. yeah. well. I did more
than hear... hear him.

1023
00:48:44.096 --> 00:48:46.431
W-We FaceTimed.

1024
00:48:46.473 --> 00:48:48.225
FaceTimed.

1025
00:48:48.266 --> 00:48:50.727
I actually saw the face

1026
00:48:50.769 --> 00:48:53.563
of the son
that I thought I had lost.

1027
00:48:53.605 --> 00:48:56.024
That's unbelievable.

1028
00:48:56.066 --> 00:48:58.151
I know. right?

1029
00:48:58.193 --> 00:49:00.403
Hey. come on.
Why don't you let me

1030
00:49:00.445 --> 00:49:02.781
- give you a ride home?
- I'm just right here...

1031
00:49:02.823 --> 00:49:04.866
- I insist.
- Okay.

1032
00:49:06.785 --> 00:49:09.496
- You're such a good friend.
- Yeah.

1033
00:49:09.538 --> 00:49:10.956
- Geez.
- <i>Matt's ashes.</i>

1034
00:49:10.997 --> 00:49:12.916
I try.

1035
00:49:12.958 --> 00:49:14.501
<i>I bet this is the closest
Matt and Kurt have ever been.</i>

1036
00:49:14.543 --> 00:49:16.128
Ah. you're good.

1037
00:49:16.169 --> 00:49:18.797
You're good and I am so lucky.

1038
00:49:19.881 --> 00:49:21.424
So lucky to...

1039
00:49:21.466 --> 00:49:24.219
be surrounded
by such great people.

1040
00:49:24.261 --> 00:49:25.804
- [Dexter chuckles]
- [laughs]

1041
00:49:25.846 --> 00:49:27.514
- [sighs]
- Especially you. Jimmy.

1042
00:49:27.556 --> 00:49:30.267
Hey. my Matty's alive!
Can you believe it?

1043
00:49:30.308 --> 00:49:31.977
[laughs]

1044
00:49:32.018 --> 00:49:33.645
[Dexter]
<i>Actually. no.</i>

1045
00:49:33.687 --> 00:49:35.313
<i>And why would he lie?</i>

1046
00:49:35.355 --> 00:49:37.315
<i>[sober music]</i>

1047
00:49:47.993 --> 00:49:49.953
<i>[gentle. mysterious music]</i>

